Via @johndownerproductions

Bottlenose dolphins are filmed apparently getting high on secretions from pufferfish. The pufferfish secrete a neurotoxin that in high doses can kill but in small doses seemingly have a narcotic effect.

Video: 'Dolphins - Spy in the Pod' narrated by David Tennant

“The first clip features a humpback whale rising from the middle of a baitball in absolutely perfect conditions! This whale's name is Snowflake. Snowflake is a very special whale to me as it is the first humpback whale I ever saw breach and the first whale that ever ‘mugged’ me…

“In the whale watching world, ‘mugging’ refers to the moment a whale sticks its head out of the water, making eye contact. Snowflake seemed to recognize our voices. It was a beautiful and life-changing moment.”

Naude Dreyer (@namib_naude) and his friend Antonie rescued this huge seal on February 26. This seal was so strong he dragged them both around and he didn’t actually fit into the net, that’s why they struggled so long to get him down! He had a very deeply embedded packing strap that must have caused immense pain. It's really amazing to see him getting rescued. Thanks to @oceanconservationnamibia .

Actual footage and A Rare Sighting of a Glass Octopus Reveals its Nearly Transparent Membrane in Extraordinary Detail⁣
⁣
On a 34-day expedition around the Phoenix Islands Archipelago, marine scientists from the Schmidt Ocean Institute captured exceptionally rare footage of the elusive glass octopus. With a speckled, iridescent membrane, the aquatic animal is almost entirely transparent—only its optic nerve, eyes, and digestive tract are visible to humans—and sightings like these are so infrequent that scientists previously resorted to studying the species only after pulling it from the stomachs of its predators.⁣
⁣

Little Squirt making its way home, as beautifully captured by @aleksmutated. 🐢 While exploring Heron Island in Queensland, you may experience some of the most unforgettable wildlife encounters that will surely leave a mark on you.⁣
⁣
If you happen to chance by in the months of January to May, you may witness turtle hatchlings emerge and make their journey to the sea. While watching, it's important to allow these young ones to make their own way to the water without any assistance or hindrance. 🙌🏼⁣
⁣
Have you ever seen turtles hatching in real life?⁣
⁣
📽 @aleksmutated⁣
📍 Heron Island, Queensland, Australia⁣

📹 @andremusgrove : One of the first ledges under the rim of the second deepest blue hole in the world, Deans Blue Hole. This ledge sits about 60ft underwater and about 25ft under the main outer rim of the blue hole. The formations in the rock somewhat resemble the inside of a human trachea however there are a few side tunnels that branch off going horizontally into the walls of the blue hole. Rumor has it may be connected to an exit point in the open ocean connected by underwater tunnels.
